&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/breach/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/breach/> ;
  schema:name "Breach" ;
  schema:description "A Breach is a triple (D, t*, p) — a duty D, an assessment deadline t*, and a performance p whose performance-and-recognition predicates have not jointly reached affirming settlement at t*. Breach is the event of a gap that should have been zero remaining positive at the assessment point. It creates immediate Hohfeldian consequences: the breaching party acquires a new duty (to remedy) and the injured party acquires new rights (to remedial acts). The settlement position of p at t* gives a four-way classification of breach by which predicate(s) failed to settle." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/breach/> ;
  rdfs:seeAlso "Duty, Commitment, Contract, Gap, Accountability, Sanction, Discharge, HohfeldianPosition, Record, Act" ;
  schema:identifier &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/breach/> .

